# apache-nifi Best Practices

This document serves as a comprehensive guide for developers working with Apache NiFi. It emphasizes practical, actionable advice, backed by concrete examples to enhance your development process.

## Code Organization and Structure

### Use Modular Process Groups
Design your NiFi flows using modular process groups. This enhances reusability and maintainability.

❌ BAD:
```plaintext
Single process group with all components mixed together.
```

✅ GOOD:
```plaintext
- Main Process Group
  - Ingest Process Group
  - Transform Process Group
  - Load Process Group
```

### Standardize Naming Conventions
Adopt a consistent naming convention for your components. This improves readability and collaboration.

❌ BAD:
```plaintext
Processor1, Processor2, MyProcessor
```

✅ GOOD:
```plaintext
- IngestCSVProcessor
- TransformDataProcessor
- LoadToDatabaseProcessor
```

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Use Parameter Contexts for Configuration
Always utilize Parameter Contexts for managing environment-specific variables and secrets.

❌ BAD:
```plaintext
- Hardcoded database credentials in the processor configuration.
```

✅ GOOD:
```plaintext
- Use Parameter Contexts to define:
  - db.username
  - db.password
```

### Ensure Thread Safety in Custom Extensions
When developing custom processors, ensure they are thread-safe due to NiFi's concurrent nature.

❌ BAD:
```java
public class MyProcessor extends AbstractProcessor {
    private List<String> state = new ArrayList<>();
    
    @Override
    public void onTrigger(ProcessContext context, ProcessSession session) {
        state.add("new state"); // Not thread-safe
    }
}
```

✅ GOOD:
```java
public class MyProcessor extends AbstractProcessor {
    private final List<String> state = Collections.synchronizedList(new ArrayList<>());

    @Override
    public void onTrigger(ProcessContext context, ProcessSession session) {
        state.add("new state"); // Thread-safe
    }
}
```

## Performance Considerations

### Optimize Processor Scheduling
Set appropriate scheduling strategies for processors to enhance performance based on the flow's requirements.

❌ BAD:
```plaintext
All processors set to run at the same time without consideration of resource usage.
```

✅ GOOD:
```plaintext
- Ingest Processor: Run on a schedule of 5 seconds.
- Transform Processor: Run on a schedule of 10 seconds.
- Load Processor: Run on a schedule of 30 seconds.
```

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Avoid Direct Edits in Production
Never make direct edits to the NiFi flow in production. Use version control through Apache NiFi Registry.

❌ BAD:
```plaintext
Editing the flow directly in the production environment.
```

✅ GOOD:
```plaintext
- Clone the flow to a staging environment.
- Test changes thoroughly.
- Commit to NiFi Registry and deploy to production.
```

### Use Git-Based Workflows
Implement Git-based workflows for managing changes to your NiFi flows. This ensures auditability and prevents configuration drift.

❌ BAD:
```plaintext
Changes made directly in the NiFi UI without tracking.
```

✅ GOOD:
```plaintext
- Use Git to track changes:
  - Commit changes to a feature branch.
  - Merge to main after review.
```

## Testing Approaches

### Use Maven for Testing
When testing your NiFi custom processors, always use `mvn clean install` to ensure no stale artifacts.

❌ BAD:
```plaintext
Running tests without cleaning the build first.
```

✅ GOOD:
```bash
mvn clean install
```

### Document Your Processors
Utilize the `additionalDetails.html` file within your processor bundle to document functionality and usage.

❌ BAD:
```plaintext
No documentation for custom processors.
```

✅ GOOD:
```html
<!-- additionalDetails.html -->
<h1>IngestCSVProcessor</h1>
<p>This processor ingests CSV files from a specified directory.</p>
```

## Conclusion
By adhering to these best practices, you will enhance the maintainability, performance, and reliability of your Apache NiFi flows. Always prioritize modularity, standardization, and thorough documentation in your development process.